	<div class="blog-archive-entries-wrapper">
		<div id="unique-entry-id-396" class="blog-entry"><h1 class="blog-entry-title">Authors Visiting</h1><div class="blog-entry-date">Wednesday, 30 March 2011 Filed in: <span class="blog-entry-category"><a href="category-books.php">Books</a></span><span class="blog-entry-category"> <a href="category-justin-somper.php">Justin Somper</a></span></div><div class="blog-entry-body"><div class="image-left"><img class="imageStyle" alt="books" src="books.jpg" width="42" height="40" /></div>Oxford is enjoying authors visiting over the next few weeks.  This Saturday Anthony Horowitz is visiting Waterstones at one o'clock and the following Saturday Justin Somper will be visiting Corpus Christi College at two o'clock (cost &pound;5) as one of the authors appearing for the Oxford Literary Festival.<br />Please see <a href="http://www.waterstones.com/waterstonesweb/displayDetailEvent.do?searchType=1&author=Anthony|Horowitz" rel="self" title="http://www.waterstones.com/events">www.waterstones.com/</a> and <a href="http://www.oxfordliteraryfestival.com/" rel="self" title="http://www.oxfordliteraryfestival.com/">www.oxfordliteraryfestival.com/</a> for more information.<br /><br />Justin Somper wrote on Twitter "Having a great time at Bologna Book Fair. Great city, loads of sun, fab food, fun crowd AND lots of chances to practice my Italiano!".  So it is not just us fans that enjoy these events.<br /></div></div><div id="unique-entry-id-395" class="blog-entry"><h1 class="blog-entry-title">Oxford Literary Festival</h1><div class="blog-entry-date">Monday, 21 March 2011 Filed in: <span class="blog-entry-category"><a href="category-books.php">Books</a></span><span class="blog-entry-category"> <a href="category-justin-somper.php">Justin Somper</a></span></div><div class="blog-entry-body"><div class="image-left"><img class="imageStyle" alt="vampirates" src="vampirates.jpg" width="40" height="40" /></div>Justin Somper wrote on Twitter: <br />"Nice mention in today's Sunday Times of my event at Oxford Literary Festival on April 9th - more info at <a href="http://www.oxfordliteraryfestival.com/" rel="self" title="http://www.oxfordliteraryfestival.com/">www.oxfordliteraryfestival.com/</a>"<br /><br />The 2011 Festival will present the most impressive and prestigious programme yet staged at Oxford - more than 550 speakers over 9 days at Christ Church, Corpus Christi and Merton Colleges.<br />Event 843 is Justin Somper at the Corpus Christi College, on 9th April at 2:00pm, cost of &pound;5, Suitable for 10+ <br />"Justin Somper&rsquo;s high-octane Vampirates sequence, fusing pirate adventure and vampire myth, is published in 34 countries and 24 languages. Anthony Horowitz said of it, &lsquo;Totally original ... I wish I&rsquo;d had this idea!&rsquo;  Hear Justin talk about the world of Vampirates in this highly interactive session, and enjoy a sneak preview of Immortal War, the sixth and final book in the sequence, ahead of its publication in June. Find out more and read Justin&rsquo;s blog, at www.vampirates.co.uk or follow him at www.twitter.com/JustinSomper. <br /></div></div><div id="unique-entry-id-393" class="blog-entry"><h1 class="blog-entry-title">Red Nose Day</h1><div class="blog-entry-date">Friday, 18 March 2011 Filed in: <span class="blog-entry-category"><a href="category-pirates.php">Pirates</a></span></div><div class="blog-entry-body"><div class="image-left"><img class="imageStyle" alt="Captain Conk" src="Sq_RND.jpg" width="40" height="40" /></div>Did you get to dress up today?  My kids and most of the school were pirates so I am sure there were loads of 'Pirate Academy' schools in the United kingdom today full of pirates<br /><br />For anyone who does not know Comic Relief has announced the next Red Nose Day will be 18th March 2011 and one of the noses they have released is Captain Conk the pirate.  Every two years the UK comedians help raise money to help make a difference to peoples lives both in the UK and abroad (predominantly in Africa).  So for the &pound;1 spent to buy either a Captain Conk red nose from Sainsbury's or Captain Conk pen from Ryman's, half of the profits goes to UK and half to Africa.  (Just a note on the nose boxes it says "with at least 70p going to Comic Relief" and the pens have "Ryman will donate &pound;1 for each pen sold.")<br />Please see <a href="http://www.rednoseday.com/" rel="self" title="http://www.rednoseday.com/">http://www.rednoseday.com/</a> for more information.<br /><br /></div></div><div id="unique-entry-id-394" class="blog-entry"><h1 class="blog-entry-title">Twitter</h1><div class="blog-entry-date">Thursday, 17 March 2011 Filed in: <span class="blog-entry-category"><a href="category-justin-somper.php">Justin Somper</a></span></div><div class="blog-entry-body"><div class="image-left"><img class="imageStyle" alt="" src="page73_blog_entry394_1.jpg" width="48" height="48" /></div>Did you know @JustinSomper was on Twitter? here are two of his latest tweets.<br /><br />"Interesting to see that University of Hertfordshire now has a Vampire module on its MA in modern literary studies. Bring it on!"<br /><br />"Great news that the Cutty Sark restoration is moving on and the ship will be open to the public again next Spring. Look forward to visiting."<br /></div></div><div id="unique-entry-id-392" class="blog-entry"><h1 class="blog-entry-title">Alex Rider</h1><div class="blog-entry-date">Monday, 07 March 2011 Filed in: <span class="blog-entry-category"><a href="category-books.php">Books</a></span></div><div class="blog-entry-body"><div class="image-left"><img class="imageStyle" alt="books" src="books.jpg" width="42" height="40" /></div>For those of you who read the Alex Rider series of books by Anthony Horowitz the trailer for the new book Scorpia Rising is now out.<br />Please see it on youtube at http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0c9Y-ai5oZw and http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5gpR8cBThWk<br />or the shortened url <a href="http://bit.ly/gSNR6G" rel="self" title="http://bit.ly/gSNR6G">http://bit.ly/gSNR6G</a><br /></div></div><div id="unique-entry-id-391" class="blog-entry"><h1 class="blog-entry-title">Twitter</h1><div class="blog-entry-date">Thursday, 03 March 2011 Filed in: <span class="blog-entry-category"><a href="category-books.php">Books</a></span></div><div class="blog-entry-body"><div class="image-left"><img class="imageStyle" alt="books" src="books.jpg" width="42" height="40" /></div>Ok it has taken me a little while to get into Twitter, but now I can access it on an app, instead of the computer, I can understand the appeal.<br />Here is something that The Guardian Guide wrote today.<br />"To celebrate @<a href="http://twitter.com/WorldBookDayUK" rel="self" title="http://twitter.com/WorldBookDayUK">WorldBookDayUK</a>, the Guardian is launching a new children's books site <a href="http://bit.ly/fy7pT9" rel="self" title="http://bit.ly/fy7pT9">http://bit.ly/fy7pT9</a> <a href="http://twitter.com/#%21/search?q=%23worldbookday" rel="self" title="http://twitter.com/#%21/search?q=%23worldbookday">#worldbookday</a>"<br />I am all for more people getting the chance to read and I wish it good luck.<br /></div></div>
	</div>
	
	 
